# Google Apps Script Core Rule

Follow these standards when generating or changing code in this repository.

## Runtime Constraints

- Target Google Apps Script runtime APIs; do not assume Node runtime APIs are available.
- Do not use filesystem access in Apps Script code.
- Avoid unsupported browser APIs in server-side code.
- Keep dependencies minimal and compatible with Apps Script execution limits.

## Code Organization

- Keep Apps Script entry points in `main.ts` (for example `doGet`, `onOpen`, `onEdit`).
- Put business logic in `services/`.
- Keep reusable helpers in `utils/`.
- Keep sheet access helpers separate from domain logic.

## Google Sheets Performance

- Batch reads and writes whenever possible.
- Do not call `getRange` inside write loops when a single `setValues` call can be used.
- Minimize API calls inside loops.

## Configuration and Secrets

- Never hardcode secrets, tokens, or environment-specific IDs.
- Use `PropertiesService` for configuration and sensitive values.
- Keep constants limited to safe, non-secret values.

## UI and Error Handling

- Use HTML Service for UI surfaces and `google.script.run` for client-server calls.
- Return safe, user-friendly error messages to the frontend.
- Do not expose stack traces, secrets, or raw sensitive responses to users.

## Security and Reliability

- Validate inputs from sidebars, dialogs, forms, and web app requests.
- Avoid logging sensitive user or business data.
- Prefer least-privilege behavior and safe defaults for data-changing operations.

## Delivery Workflow

- Make small, testable changes instead of large one-shot rewrites.
- Compile TypeScript before `clasp push`.
- Call out Apps Script platform constraints when they affect implementation choices.

## Historical snapshots (cache sync)

When changing dashboard **payload shape**, **`cacheSchemaVersion`**, or server builders (`fiberyAgreementDashboard.js`, `fiberyUtilizationDashboard.js`, `deliveryDashboard.js`, client cache in `DashboardShell.html`), also follow **`.cursor/rules/dashboard-snapshot-cache-sync.mdc`**: keep `dashboardSnapshotJob.js` artifacts and `docs/features/009-dashboard-historical-snapshots.md` aligned so Drive snapshots do not drift from live caches.

## PRD change control (mandatory - FOS Dashboard)

**Every merge-worthy change** in this repo MUST include a **PRD version bump** in the **same** commit/PR as the code or docs change. Do not defer version sync to a follow-up. Do not leave changelog rows with a blank version or omit a bump.

Documentation punctuation: no em dashes (`—`). See **`.cursor/rules/documentation-style.mdc`**.

**Product PRD:** `docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md` (not `docs/PRD.md`).

### Completion checklist (required before finishing)

1. **Bump version** in `docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md`: header `**PRD version X.Y.Z**`, body line `Version X.Y.Z - <date>`, and **§13 Change Log** row with the **same** version number.
2. **`src/Code.js`:** set `FOS_PRD_VERSION` to match exactly; update `FOS_RELEASE_DESCRIPTION` (one-line release note for App Versions registry).
3. **`src/*` headers:** update the PRD version line in **every** clasp-pushed `.js` and `.html` under `src/` (exclude `appsscript.json`).
4. **Feature docs touched:** update the `> **PRD version …**` line at the top of any `docs/features/*.md` file you edit; add or extend that feature’s changelog when behavior changes.
5. **Overview:** if the product version changed, update `docs/features/000-overview.md` PRD version line when it tracks “current”.

**Block completion** if any of the above is missing while `src/` or user-visible behavior changed.

### PRD version in file headers (clasp / Apps Script)

Whenever `docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md` **version number** changes:

1. Bump **`FOS_PRD_VERSION`** in `src/Code.js` to match **exactly**.
2. Update the **PRD version line** at the top of **every** file under `src/`:
   - **JavaScript:** ` * PRD version X.Y.Z - sync with docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md`
   - **HTML:** `<!-- PRD version X.Y.Z - sync with docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md -->`
3. Same commit as the PRD bump and changelog row.

### Version-number rules (semver-style)

Use **`MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`** for `docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md`. The same number drives `FOS_PRD_VERSION` and all `src/*` headers.

| Segment | Bump when… | Examples |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **MAJOR** (`X.0.0`) | Breaking contract: auth model replaced, multi-deployment split, or breaking `google.script.run` / cache contract. **Rare**; confirm with the user first. | `2.0.0` |
| **MINOR** (`X.Y.0`) | New feature, new FR/AC, new `docs/features/` spec, new server module, or substantial new surface area. Default when unsure between “small” and “new capability.” | `2.3.0` -> `2.4.0` |
| **PATCH** (`X.Y.Z`) | Minor fix or **small** enhancement to existing behavior (copy, KPI subtext, layout tweak, bugfix, schema-path fix) without a new feature phase. **Use a patch for every shipped change** when the change is intentionally small. | `2.4.2` -> `2.4.3` |

Conventions:

- **Two-segment back-compat:** older changelog rows may show `X.Y` only; new bumps use three segments.
- **Always add a §13 changelog row** with a real version (never blank or `TBD` in the version column).
- **Patch bumps still sync all `src/*` headers** (full header sweep, not just changed files).
- **One bump per change set:** do not stack unrelated MINOR + PATCH; ship corrections as the next PATCH.
- **No leading `v`:** write `2.4.3`, not `v2.4.3`.
- **Imported / static PRDs** (e.g. `docs/implementation-notes/revenue-review-dashboard-PRD.html`) may keep their own changelog versions; still bump **FOS** `2.4.x` when the Web App ships the change.

**Other harpin Apps Script projects** (e.g. Clockify–Fibery sync): use that repo’s PRD path and version constant; apply the same “bump every change + every `src` header” discipline.

## Feature Spec Template Compliance

- All new feature documents in `docs/features/` must follow `docs/FEATURE_TEMPLATE.md`.
- Use the same section order and headings from the template unless the user explicitly requests a deviation.
- Keep template checklists as markdown checkboxes (`- [ ]`) so progress can be tracked.
- Name feature files using the existing numeric convention (for example `001-feature-name.md`).
- If a feature spec exists but does not match the template, update it to template format when making substantive edits.
